did.unittitle: Associated Students of Duke University records
did.abstract: The Associated Students of Duke University (ASDU) was the student government at Duke from 1967 to 1993. It originated in March 1967 when the student body voted to merge the Men's Student Government Association and the Women's Student Government Association. ASDU consisted of an executive branch and a legislative branch. A student referendum in April 1993 replaced ASDU with a new organization, Duke Student Government, in which the legislative and executive branches were consolidated. ASDU records consist of minutes, correspondence, legislation, reports, printed matter, judicial decisions, charters, memoranda, speeches, receipts, vouchers, and other records. The ASDU records provide insight into student life during a time when students were becoming more active in university affairs. The records also document student organizations at Duke at this time and demonstrate some of the services provided to students by ASDU.

accessrestrict.head: Access Restrictions
accessrestrict.p: Researchers must register and agree to copyright and privacy laws before using this collection.

Records of the University's Board of Trustees which have been existence for at least fifty years are available for scholarly research with the permission of the University Archivist. Access to records which have been in existence for less than fifty years shall be granted only by special permission, in writing, from the Board of Trustees.

In accordance with the Family Education Rights and Privacy Act of 1974 as amended, Duke University permits students to inspect their education records and limits the disclosure of personally identifiable information from education records.

bioghist.head: Historical Note
bioghist.p: The Associated Students of Duke University (ASDU), the student government from 1967-1993, originated in March 1967, when the student body voted to merge the Men's Student Government Association and the Women's Student Government Association. ASDU began its duties in the Fall of 1967 with Jon Kinney serving as the first President.

ASDU was divided into Executive and Legislative branches. The Executive was made up of the President, Vice President(s), other officers, and the Executive cabinet. Officers were elected to one-year terms. The President had veto power over legislation passed by the Legislature. The Legislature consisted of representatives elected by members of individual schools and colleges and met weekly. The Legislature was responsible for enacting legislation pertaining to student welfare, chartering all student organizations, and approving Presidential appointments. A President's veto could be overturned by a two-thirds majority vote. A Speaker was elected to preside over the Legislature.

A student referendum passed in April 1993 replaced ASDU with a new student government which featured the consolidation of the legislative and executive branches. The new organization was called the Duke Student Government (DSG).

scopecontent.head: Collection Overview
scopecontent.p: The records of the Associated Students of Duke University span from 1965-1991, covering the years that ASDU existed, as well as a few items prior to the establishment of ASDU in 1967. The bulk of the material focuses on the 1970s and early 1980s. The records consist of agendas and minutes, charters, correspondence and memoranda, resolutions and statutes, reports, studies, financial material, photographs, newspaper clippings and other printed matter.

The ASDU records provide insight into student life during a time when students were becoming more active in university affairs. The collection is useful in examining issues that were important to students in the 1970s and 1980s such as divestment in South Africa, financial aid and campus race relations and the actions taken on those issues; how effective student government was during this period; and also illuminates student organizations at Duke at this time -- both what they were and what they did. The records also demonstrate some of the services provided to students by ASDU: the Bail Loan Fund; Legal assistance; van/shuttle services; and the distribution of the Student Activities fee.
Additional ASDU records can be found inter-filed with Duke Student Government records. Please contact University Archives for additional information.

scopecontent.p: The Financial Materials subseries contain the records of the ASDU Treasurer and Business Manager. The series features budgetary materials for the ASDU general administration and budget requests and audits for ASDU funded student organizations. The Financial materials series also includes information about the funding of ASDU student services such as an ASDU sponsored lawyer.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The Committees series features minutes, reports, memorandum and notes compiled by ASDU committees. The ASDU Committees subseries contains the materials of committees ASDU commissioned to study an aspect of Duke undergraduate life such as financial aid, dining services, and alcohol awareness. The University Committees subseries includes the records of ASDU student representatives who served on university wide committees such as the Academic Council and Residence Life Committee. The Board of Trustees subseries consists of the records of the ASDU representative to the Board of Trustees. The Athletic Council subseries includes ASDU copies of materials produced by this influential university committee.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The ASDU Committees subseries contains the records of student committees. ASDU sponsored both standing committees such as the Academic Affairs Committee and task forces to study pressing issues such as the Task Force on Black-White Relations. The committees were usually run by ASDU officers but were also staffed by members of the general student body and task forces often appointed representatives from student groups involved with the issue studied. The committees often produced a report for the ASDU Executive Council and Duke officials summarizing the findings of the committee and suggesting future recommendations.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The University Committees subseries features the records of student members of official Duke University committees between 1965-1991. Duke undergraduates could apply to serve as ASDU representatives on committees such as the Student Affairs Trustee Committee and the Undergraduate Faculty Committee of Arts and Sciences (UFCAS). The representatives were expected to file a monthly update with the ASDU offices. Materials include meeting minutes, agendas, memorandum and official committee reports.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The Athletic Council subseries contains select records from the Athletic Council which oversaw Duke intercollegiate and club athletics. The subseries contains a series of 1972 surveys distributed to student athletes from Duke's 10 Division I intercollegiate athletic programs. The subseries also contain a 1982 report, "Recommendations on Intercollegiate Athletics", analyzes and proposes plans for the future of Duke sports teams.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The Legislature Series include chronologically organized Resolutions and Statues passed between the ASDU Legislature between 1967-1987. The series also features files of the Speaker of Legislature, the records of the Legislative Ethics Committee, copies of the ASDU constitution and successive amendments, and the by-laws of the legislature. The Legislature series also includes administrative documents such as versions of the "Guide to Parliamentary Procedure" and instructions for drafting bills.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The Minutes Series contains meeting minutes from sessions of the ASDU Legislature and Executive Council from 1967-1989. The records provide information about the issues discussed at these meetings, committee reports and the resolutions and decisions that occurred.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The Subject Files series contains memorandum, reports, clippings and other materials related to a number of ASDU initiatives. The series is arranged alphabetically. Topics include alcohol and drug policies, housing policies and dining services. Also included is information related the Social Impact of Duke Investments campaign against companies that supported apartheid in South Africa, including student letters asking the administration and Board of Trustees to end support.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The General Materials series contains additional information about the structure and initiatives of ASDU. The Administrative Materials subseries contains internal planning and evaluation documents and other materials collected and used by ASDU officers. The Publications and Reports subseries includes materials published and used by ASDU such as committee reports, copies of the Student Directory and the ASDU Update newsletter.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The Administrative Materials subseries includes information about ASDU elections and referendums, the history of ASDU and materials related to membership in regional and national student organizations. The subseries also contains copies of the ASDU constitution, information about the 1979 re-organization and other miscellaneous documents.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The Publications and Reports subseries compiles materials ASDU published and distributed or used as references for decision making. These materials include copies of committee and task force reports from both ASDU and University committees, student handbooks and directories, ASDU newsletters. This subseries also contains clippings from The Chronicle discussing ASDU and other miscellaneous materials.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The Executive series contains materials gathered by executive officers of ASDU who serving in the years 1972 to 1990. Materials include correspondence, reports, memorandum, minutes and committee information. The Presidential Files subseries contains materials from the presidents of ASDU and the Executive Files subseries contains records produced by other executive positions. The Executive Council subseries contains the records of the main executive committee.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The Presidential Files subseries contains the correspondence, reports, notes and memorandum from ASDU presidents. The subseries is arranged chronologically by presidential administration with the bulk of the records dating from the early 1980s. Many of the files contain communications with Duke administrators including Terry Sanford, H. Kenneth Pye and William Griffiths. Also included are presidential speeches and addresses and a set of papers entitled "To the Next ASDU President" in which presidents gave advice on the responsibilities of the position to their successor.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The Executive Files subseries contains correspondence, reports, notes and memorandum gathered by the executive officers of ASDU including the Vice-President at Large, Student Organizations Chairman, and Executive Secretary. The subseries is arranged alphabetically by position title. The papers contain information about the responsibilities of each executive position, current initiatives and working relationships between executives.
